## Architecture Reference (Aspirational Patterns)

@ARCHITECTURE.md

## Project Structure & Module Organization

- `app/` holds Rails code (models, controllers, views, jobs, aspects).
- `spec/` contains RSpec tests (e.g., `spec/models`, `spec/requests`).
- `config/` stores Rails configuration, including `config/ci.rb` and `config/database.yml`.
- `db/` has migrations and schema; `storage/` is for Active Storage.
- Frontend assets use import maps (`config/importmap.rb`) and SASS via `dartsass-rails`.

## Development Commands

This project uses [mise](https://mise.jdx.dev/) to manage the Ruby version and gem paths.

### Setup and Server

- `bin/setup` installs gems, prepares the database, and starts dev services.
- `bin/dev` runs the Procfile (`Procfile.dev`) with a Rails server and SASS watcher.

### Testing

- `bin/rspec` runs the full test suite
- `bin/rspec spec/path/file_spec.rb` runs a single test file
- `bin/ci` runs style and security checks (Rubocop, bundler-audit, importmap audit, Brakeman)

### Linting

- `bin/rubocop` should not show any errors or warnings. If rubocop shows errors that are
  auto-correctable, fix them with `bin/rubocop -A {files}` instead of editing them manually.
- `mise exec -- bunx oxlint app/javascript/` should not show any errors or warnings
- `mise exec -- bunx stylelint "app/assets/stylesheets/**/*.{css,scss}"` should not show any errors or warnings
- `bin/reek .` Run it against the files you changed and consider any new issues (see note below).
  The command `bin/reek .` runs the full check (bare `bin/reek` defaults to scanning `.` only when
  stdin is a TTY, which is not the case in agent runners).

#### A note about the Reek linter

Unlike Rubocop or Oxlint, an issue flagged by Reek is usually not a small problem with a quick fix,
or something to add to the ignore list without considering. For example, "TooManyMethods" means the
class is too large, and probably needs to be broken up into smaller parts. A component with many
slot helper methods might indicate a missing sub-component that could encapsulate more generic
rendering behavior.

For a description of every smell, example code, and concrete fix strategies, see @REEK.md.

If you see an issue flagged by Reek in your code, and you're not sure what the fix is, STOP AND ASK.
DO NOT suppress it in `.reek.yml` without discussing it. NEVER add inline `:reek:` comments.

### Database

- `bin/rails db:reset` Drop, create, re-run migrations, seed
- `bin/rails db:prepare` Initializes or migrates the database.

When adding migrations, do not write the file directly. Instead, use `bin/rails
generate migration NameOfMigration` and edit the file. This uses our template with better defaults,
and avoids an issue with the timestamp in the filename generated by agents.

